 shouldn't. I could consider avoiding annotation on the entire test class. Alternatively, it might make sense to create a separate public top-level class named TemplateSpringTest in its own file and then test the scanner in TestClassScannerTest. But is that a one-to-one mapping?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_vxxRJnz0lhz8Uuv4bwHdGC6e|fc_0189db8303069f10016a29d48ae11c8196bf63084122a1e2a5", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/build -path '*compileClasspath*' -o -path '*runtimeClasspath*' | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1580, "output": 1789, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37161, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781126237627, "responseId": "resp_0189db8303069f10016a29d45e23788196b8e82e06d211f491"}}
