[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test structure**\n\nI’m thinking about how the scanner might call scan within the test method. If it discovers the same class template, that could instantiate the provider without issues. The class has @ContextConfiguration, which suggests it’s a generic Spring test, but no SpringExtension is present. So, the actual test doesn’t load Spring, which seems fine. I wonder if the test class itself could also have a @Test method, and if nested @Nested classes might be executed as well.\n\n**Evaluating JUnit issues**\n\nI'm thinking about a potential problem where a test class annotated with @ClassTemplate has nested @Nested classes without any test methods. I wonder if JUnit would fail with a \"No tests discovered\" message for the nested classes, but typically, it shouldn't. I could consider avoiding annotation on the entire test class. Alternatively, it might make sense to create a separate public top-level class named TemplateSpringTest in its own file and then test the scanner in TestClassScannerTest. But is that a one-to-one mapping?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0189db8303069f10016a29d45f2f788196a418e99353bbbfee\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKdSKaqa8HPcz9MFFtYPYW4j9SJbSzKmp3zWGo_KHVppk5wVo_bkEpkj4V73OTVLjmVHCzs3UjAGXeSSzOt7v4khczpZhbA31TbUcqaUfb87alZccZJos2CFTgSkKgSgd4RFKSTlZ_q4jiMMt_GnfcCXqv91TuJ7oY6xCOH6PCnlTguHGo0fAQFQ2Sz12L4rK_XCr1eRDU5gwt8K-_LMfk65Mee0DQNUsWc3k8TqDbRmS3OiUkes2c9HN4y7zuj8yMoGdkZqCt6BILl3UX3Mcghu-SbWUMuAAA6r0UHjIzKS_Hr7G1AXDv4ZW1G2PMJlS1B5OZXQF7-H37j8OcmUsAwAKlZQaoj_pTNmW_8OhNMm2bl3ZU37UseZYk7ZURGLApkP4wIPu4IM8CAawqH8lFMx148VZw57sY6vsAhDBNleeNqnbt5_d2KYJIECCfodTmOxT_rCjsoJprvRIYAKI5CRZM6nYFRJ7-3mYcL0O5K991Qp_6PxicsZ8JMbINbuSH6OjX5wXroSpaYOI1WRsJvA6dFwRJ-HHua8QrIw_SZ1zgzLKqI-8_x5fdloKT6XoBMHtp4Cg1M6euWfYv0I0ICyQeMCwBOWRNz2u85OgH7812ri-oPgY8M6MTCxSRDMAEu_u39-Oy23-X-h8QeEm5rtRss1IsWts